Peer assessment may be fair for university course evaluations if properly organized and managed. Peer evaluation fairness depends on various factors: Training: Peers should learn how to provide helpful comments and assess work objectively. Guidelines: Students should be given clear criteria for how their peers will judge their work. Anonymity: Anonymous peer evaluation removes personal ties and other non-academic elements to prevent prejudice and assure impartiality. The instructor should be engaged to guarantee accurate and fair feedback. Students may also get help from the instructor. Self-assessment: Students may evaluate their work before peer review and indicate areas for improvement, ensuring fairness. Peer assessment should be used in conjunction with other techniques, such as examinations, quizzes, and assignments, to evaluate student learning. Peer evaluation has drawbacks include prejudice, inexperience, and inconsistent input. 